{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492749"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:43:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:43:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1148"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1148"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.04,0.09,0.13,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1148"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83516"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1148"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1148"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68389"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"651"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4023"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5065"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1765"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2042"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28365"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83516"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with weakness shortly after being started on a thiazide diuretic. Her serum potassium is 1.9 mmol/L. It is crucial to correct this and identify any other possible concurrent electrolyte imbalances.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important to identify when correcting her hypokalaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypomagnesaemia","Hypermagnesaemia","Hypercalcaemia","Hypernatraemia","Hyponatraemia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUncorrected \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypomagnesaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can result in hypokalaemia that is refractory to potassium replacement. Magnesium is a cofactor for the Na/K-ATPase pump, and so magnesium deficit decreases the activity of this channel. This reduces the intracellular uptake of potassium, allowing for potassium wasting where gastrointestinal or renal losses are increased. Decreased magnesium also results in disinhibition of ROMK channels of the principal cells in the kidney, resulting in increased potassium secretion and renal potassium losses. These mechanisms render hypomagnesaemia an important consideration in the correction of hypokalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThiazide diuretics can also result in \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyponatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E. However, neither hyponatraemia nor hypercalcaemia will perpetuate potassium losses in this setting, as the loss of potassium occurs secondary to increased delivery of sodium to the distal tubule due to the action of the thiazide diuretic. However, hypokalaemia can cause difficulty in correction of hyponatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypomagnesaemia can be complicated by refractory hypokalaemia.","Magnesium is a cofactor for the Na/K-ATPase pump, influencing potassium homeostasis.","Thiazide diuretics can lead to electrolyte imbalances, including hypokalaemia and hypomagnesaemia."],"references":["Cohn JN, Kowey PR, Whelton PK, Prisant LM. New guidelines for potassium replacement in clinical practice: a contemporary review by the National Council on Potassium in Clinical Practice. Arch Intern Med. 2000 Sep 11;160(16):2429-36. doi: 10.1001/archinte.160.16.2429. PMID: 10979053. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10979053/","Huang CL, Kuo E. Mechanism of hypokalemia in magnesium deficiency. J Am Soc Nephrol. 2007 Oct;18(10):2649-52. doi: 10.1681/ASN.2007070792. Epub 2007 Sep 5. PMID: 17804670. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17804670/","Longo AL, Kasper DL, Jameson JL, Fauci AS, Hauser SL, Loscalzo J, editors. Harrison\u2019s principles of internal medicine, 18th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill Professional; 2012.","Liamis G, Filippatos TD, Elisaf MS. Thiazide-associated hyponatremia in the elderly: what the clinician needs to know. J Geriatr Cardiol. 2016 Feb;13(2):175-82. doi: 10.11909/j.issn.1671-5411.2016.02.001. PMID: 27168745; PMCID: PMC4854958. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27168745/","Funder JW, Carey RM, Mantero F, Murad MH, Reincke M, Shibata H, Stowasser M, Young WF Jr. The Management of Primary Aldosteronism: Case Detection, Diagnosis, and Treatment: An Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2016 May;101(5):1889-916. doi: 10.1210/jc.2015-4061. Epub 2016 Mar 2. PMID: 26934393. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26934393/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68389"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1148"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68389"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-04T21:00:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-04T21:00:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1148"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83516"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"